04203nam a22005415i 9780226336008DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226336008  a(DE-B1597)524345  a(OCoLC)1125190713  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQH83b.K46 2016 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a572.838223  aWH 90002rvk1 aKemp, T. S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Origin of Higher Taxa :bPalaeobiological, Developmental, and Ecological Perspectives /cT. S. Kemp. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b25 halftones, 75 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The nature of higher taxa -- t3. The nature of organisms -- t4. The palaeontological evidence -- t5. The developmental evidence -- t6. The ecological perspective -- t7. The invertebrate fossil record -- t8. The vertebrate fossil record -- t9. A synthesis -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the grand sweep of evolution, the origin of radically new kinds of organisms in the fossil record is the result of a relatively simple process: natural selection marching through the ages. Or is it? Does Darwinian evolution acting over a sufficiently long period of time really offer a complete explanation, or are unusual genetic events and particular environmental and ecological circumstances also involved? With The Origin of Higher Taxa, Tom Kemp sifts through the layers of paleobiological, genetic, and ecological evidence on a quest to answer this essential, game-changing question of biology. Looking beyond the microevolutionary force of Darwinian natural selection, Kemp enters the realm of macroevolution, or evolution above the species level. From the origin of mammals to the radiation of flowering plants, these large-scale patterns—such as the rise of novel organismal design, adaptive radiations, and lineage extinctions—encompass the most significant trends and transformations in evolution. As macroevolution cannot be studied by direct observation and experiment, scientists have to rely on the outcome of evolution as evidence for the processes at work, in the form of patterns of species appearances and extinctions in a spotty fossil record, and through the nature of species extant today. Marshalling a wealth of new fossil and molecular evidence and increasingly sophisticated techniques for their study, Kemp here offers a timely and original reinterpretation of how higher taxa such as arthropods, mollusks, mammals, birds, and whales evolved—a bold new take on the history of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBiologyvClassification. 0aEvolution (Biology). 70(DE-601)1060986830(DE-588)4071051-8aEvolutionstheorie2gnd 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aKemp, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022633581040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226336008423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226336008/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles